A RESOLUTION
1 Honoring the memory of Mrs. Rosa Parks and recognizing February 4, 2025, as Rosa Parks
2 Day at the state capitol; and for other purposes.
3 WHEREAS, on December 1, 1955, seamstress Rosa Parks became a beacon of courage and
4 a symbol of the Civil Rights Movement when she refused to give up her seat on a city bus
5 to a white passenger, accepting arrest, trial, and conviction rather than humiliation; and
6 WHEREAS, her quiet insistence on human dignity in the face of segregation, racism, and
7 Jim Crow laws sparked the city-wide bus boycott in Montgomery, Alabama, that brought an
8 unknown young minister, Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., to national prominence; and
9 WHEREAS, alongside Dr. King, Rosa Parks became a leader and an icon in the national
10 effort that resulted in the United States Supreme Court decision outlawing the segregation
11 of city buses and gave critical momentum to the larger battle for civil rights; and
12 WHEREAS, Rosa Parks has been hailed as the "Mother of the Civil Rights Movement" in
13 America for her pivotal act on that day in Alabama, as well as for her lifelong commitment
14 to justice for Black Americans; and
